summary:
In my research, I aim to positively contribute to men's and women's health. As a graduate student in psychology, I wrote a report on gender differences in work disability and the report was widely disseminated by FNV Vrouwenbond. That is when I learned how important a good translation of scientific work is to different target groups through different channels. I worked shortly as a policymaker in the women's movement and soon started my PhD trajectory on the implementation of sex and gender issues in all Dutch medical curricula. Currently, my research focus is on interculturalization/ diversity issues in health care and medical education and from an intersectionality perspective. I published and submitted work on sex, gender and occupational health for instance on work-related fatigue among Dutch highly educated women, and participated in several EU projects (e.g. development of a Summer School Gender Medicine in the EUGiM project; the development of a website/database with good practices on gender and health in the Engender project; the Eugenmed project, the C2ME project Erasmus LLP), and in a ZonMW-project the role of early health indicators, SES, and gender in school drop out. Currently, I (co-)lead and participate in projects on Diversity in Health Care and on Diversity in Health Care Teams, on women's occupational health and female specific lifestages (ZonMw, WOMEN Inc.), on informal carers with a migrant background (NWO), and on the health of informal carers, volunteers and workers in elderly care (ZonMw). I am the secretary of the Nederlandse Vereniging Gender & Gezondheid (NVG&G, www.genderengezondheid.nl). I teach gender and diversity issues in health and illness in medical education and in the health sciences curriculum. 

Specialties: Interculturalization and gender diversity in medical education;  
sex and gender issues in public health, in particular occupational health; intersectionality and health (care)
